{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510264"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:27:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:27:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11514"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11514"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.04,0.56,0.34,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4145"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101664"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4145","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4145"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11514"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84116"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5210"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5255"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12812"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13742"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34655"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35249"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35272"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101664"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of increasing confusion and anxiety. He has a medical history of major depressive disorder, chronic pancreatitis, and alcohol-use disorder. His regular medications are sertraline and pancreatic enzyme supplements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears confused and malnourished. His pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 12/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. His abdomen is grossly distended.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following physical examination findings is most likely to be present in the current presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Non-pitting oedema of lower limbs","Velvety papillomas in intertriginous sites","Shifting dullness","Low-amplitude tremor","Pyoderma gangrenosum"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs and symptoms suggestive of hepatic encephalopathy, likely due to cirrhosis from chronic alcohol use. The key physical examination findings in this case are related to the complications of cirrhosis, particularly ascites and hepatic encephalopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShifting dullness\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely physical examination finding to be present in this patient. It is a sign of ascites, which is a common complication of cirrhosis due to portal hypertension. To elicit shifting dullness, the examiner percusses from midline to the left flank. Upon detecting a dull percussion note, the patient is rolled towards the examiner, and the area is re-percussed after 30 seconds. The sign is positive if the percussion changes from dull to resonant, indicating a shift in the ascitic fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-pitting oedema\u003C/strong\u003E of lower limbs is not typically associated with cirrhosis. Cirrhosis can cause peripheral oedema, but it is usually pitting due to hypoalbuminaemia. Non-pitting oedema is more commonly seen in conditions like lymphoedema or hypothyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVelvety papillomas\u003C/strong\u003E in intertriginous sites describe acanthosis nigricans, which is associated with metabolic and endocrine disorders such as type 2 diabetes mellitus, obesity, and acromegaly. It is not a typical finding in cirrhosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow-amplitude tremor\u003C/strong\u003E is not characteristic of hepatic encephalopathy. In hepatic encephalopathy, asterixis may be present, which is a coarse flapping tremor of the outstretched, dorsiflexed hands. Low-amplitude tremors are more commonly seen in essential tremors or enhanced physiologic tremors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPyoderma gangrenosum\u003C/strong\u003E is a type of neutrophilic dermatosis presenting as inflammatory ulcers. It is most commonly associated with inflammatory bowel disease or arthritis, not with cirrhosis or alcohol use disorder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to shifting dullness, other physical examination findings that might be present in this patient include abdominal distension, fluid thrill (other signs of ascites), jaundice, spider angiomas, palmar erythema, and asterixis (signs of hepatic encephalopathy). The patient\u0027s confusion and altered mental status are also consistent with hepatic encephalopathy, a common complication of cirrhosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cirrhosis causes portal hypertension and resultant complications (decompensation) such as hepatic encephalopathy, ascites, oesophageal varices, and spontaneous bacterial peritonitis.","Physical examination findings of ascites include abdominal distension, shifting dullness and fluid thrill.","Signs and symptoms of hepatic encephalopathy include altered mental status and asterixis, a coarse flapping tremor of the outstretched, dorsiflexed hands."],"references":["Talley NJ, O\u2019Connor S. The gastrointestinal system. In: Talley NJ, editor. Clinical examination: a systematic guide to physical diagnosis. 6th ed. Chatswood (NSW): Elsevier; 2014. p. 145-197","Gin\u00e8s P, Krag A, Abraldes JG, Sol\u00e0 E, Fabrellas N, Kamath PS. Liver cirrhosis. Lancet. 2021 Oct 9;398(10308):1359\u201376."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84116"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11514"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84116"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-03T21:26:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-03T21:27:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4145"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101664"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":